          "block_order": 12
        }
      ],
      "markdown": "(b) Construct a matrix that has column $1+2(column3)=0$  Check that A is singularewis)exliwht mustbta.\n\n### 1.27 True or false, with reason if true and counterexampeif false:\n\n(1) If $L_{1}U_{1}=L_{2}U_{2}$ (upper triangular $U^{\\prime}s$ with nonzero diagonal, lower triangular $L^{\\prime}\\mathrm{s}$ with unit diagonal), then $L_{1}=L_{2}\\ and\\ U_{1}=U_{2}$ . The LU factorization is unique.\n\n\n\n(2)$\\operatorname{I f}A^{2}+A=I\\operatorname{t h e n}A^{-1}=A+I.$ \n\n(3) If all diagonal entries of A are zero, then A is singular.\n\n### 1.28 By experiment or the Gauss-Jordan method compute \n\n$$\\begin{array}{r l r l r}{\\left[\\begin{matrix}{1}&{0}&{0}\\\\ {\\ell}&{1}&{0}\\\\ {m}&{0}&{1}\\end{matrix}\\right]^{n},}&{{}}&{\\left[\\begin{matrix}{1}&{0}&{0}\\\\ {\\ell}&{1}&{0}\\\\ {m}&{0}&{1}\\end{matrix}\\right]^{-1},}&{{}}&{\\left[\\begin{matrix}{1}&{0}&{0}\\\\ {\\ell}&{1}&{0}\\\\ {0}&{m}&{1}\\end{matrix}\\right]^{-1}.}\\end{array}$$\n\n### 1.29 Write down the 2 by 2 matrices that \n\n(a) reverse the direction of every vector.\n\n(b) project every vector onto the $x_{2}$ axis.\n\n(c) turn every vector counterclockwise through 90°.\n\n(d) reflect every vector through the 45° line $x_{1}=x_{2}$ ",
